 | name=鹿苑神社
 | image=[[File:Rokuon-jinja, haiden-1.jpg|270px]]<br/>拝殿<br />{{maplink2|frame=yes|plain=yes|type=point|zoom=13|marker=religious-shinto|frame-align=center|frame-width=270|coord={{coord|34|42|31.9|N|137|51|30.9|E}}}}
 | location=[[Shizuoka Prefecture|Shizuoka]] [[Iwata]] Ninomiya 1767
 | 位置={{Coord|34|42|31.9|N|137|51|30.9|E|region:JP-22_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}
 | deity={{ill|Ōkuninushi|ja|大国主|lt=Ōnamuchi no Mikoto|12=draft|12=draft}}
 | type={{ill|Shikinaisha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|12=draft|12=draft}}（小）<br/>{{ill|Tōtōmi Province|ja|遠江国|12=draft|12=draft}} {{ill|Ninomiya (Shinto)|ja|二宮|12=draft|12=draft}}<br/>旧{{ill|Gōsha|ja|郷社|12=draft|12=draft}}
 | 創建=(伝) [[履中天皇|Emperor Richū]] 4th year 
 | 本殿={{ill|Hachiman-zukuri|ja|八幡造|12=draft|12=draft}}銅板葺
 | festival=1st Sunday of October
 | 地図 = {{location map|Japan Shizuoka|label=Rokuon Shrine|float=center|relief=1|width=200|caption=}}
}}
'''Rokuon Shrine''' (鹿苑神社) is a [[Shinto shrine]] located in Ninomiya, [[Iwata]], [[Shizuoka Prefecture]]. It is classified as a {{ill|Shikinaisha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|12=draft|12=draft}}, the second shrine (Ninomiya) of [[Tōtōmi Province]], and was previously ranked as a {{ill|Gōsha|ja|郷社|12=draft|12=draft}} under the old shrine ranking system.

To the north, it borders Renpuku-ji Temple, and it is situated southeast of [[Iwata Station]] and south of the Yokosuka Highway. The shrine crest is the "Sixteen Chrysanthemums." Until the late [[Edo period]], it was known as "Takane Myōjinja" and enshrined {{ill|Ajisukitakahikone|ja|アヂスキタカヒコネ|lt=Takahikone no Mikoto|12=draft|12=draft}}.

== History ==

The shrine is identified with the {{ill|Kashikojinja|ja|鹿神社|12=draft|12=draft}} mentioned as a minor shrine in the {{ill|Engishiki|ja|延喜式神名帳|12=draft|12=draft}} for Iwata District. The deity of Rokuon Shrine was granted the Junior Fifth Rank in {{ill|Kashō (Japan)|ja|嘉祥|12=draft|12=draft}} 3 (850 CE)<ref>『{{ill|Nihon Montoku Tennō Jitsuroku|ja|日本文徳天皇実録|12=draft|12=draft}}』 嘉祥3rd year {{ill|7月11日 (旧暦)|ja|7月11日|12=draft|12=draft}}（850th year 8月25日）条</ref> and was further elevated to the Junior Fourth Rank in {{ill|Jōgan (Japan)|ja|貞観|12=draft|12=draft}} 2 (860 CE)<ref>『{{ill|Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|ja|日本三代実録|12=draft|12=draft}}』 貞観2nd year {{ill|1月27日 (旧暦)|ja|正月27日|12=draft|12=draft}}（860th year 2月26日）条</ref>. It was originally located in Yorigo, Sanka District (modern-day Haruno, {{ill|Tenryū-ku|ja|天竜区|12=draft|12=draft}}, [[Hamamatsu]]), near the {{ill|Seikoku Rokuon Daibosatsu|ja|正国六音大菩薩社|12=draft|12=draft}}<ref>『遠江国風土記伝』</ref>. During the {{ill|Gangyō era|ja|元慶|12=draft|12=draft}} 5 (881 CE), the shrine was moved near the provincial capital of Tōtōmi when Sanka District was separated from Iwata District.

By the [[Kamakura period]], the shrine was referred to as Ninomiya. Records from {{ill|Bunei era|ja|文永|12=draft|12=draft}} 5 (1268 CE) mention shrine lands under "Tōtōmi Province's Ninomiya Domain."<ref>『基重言上状』</ref> During the [[Edo period]], the shrine served as the [[sōchinju]] for 14 villages, including Ninomiya Village. In the 9th year of {{ill|Genna (Japan)|ja|元和|12=draft|12=draft}} (1623 CE), the shrine buildings were rebuilt, as indicated by surviving {{ill|mune-fuda|ja|棟札|12=draft|12=draft}}. In the first year of {{ill|Keian era|ja|慶安|12=draft|12=draft}} (1648 CE), the shrine was granted 23 koku of land.

