'''Rokuon Shrine''' (鹿苑神社) is a [[Shinto shrine]] located in Ninomiya, [[Iwata]], [[Shizuoka Prefecture]]. It is classified as a {{ill|Shikinaisha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the second shrine (Ninomiya) of [[Tōtōmi Province]], and was previously Ranked as a {{ill|Gōsha|ja|郷社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} under the old shrine Ranking system.

To the north, it borders Renpuku-ji Temple, and it is situated southeast of [[Iwata Station]] and south of the Yokosuka Highway. The shrine crest is the "Sixteen Chrysanthemums." Until the late [[Edo period]], it was known as "Takane Myōjinja" and enshrined {{ill|Ajisukitakahikone|ja|アヂスキタカヒコネ|lt=Takahikone no Mikoto|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

== History ==

The shrine is identified with the {{ill|Kashikojinja|ja|鹿神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} mentioned as a minor shrine in the {{ill|Engishiki|ja|延喜式神名帳|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyocho|qq=draft|qq=draft}} for Iwata District. The deity of Rokuon Shrine was granted the Junior Fifth Rank in {{ill|Kashō (Japan)|ja|嘉祥|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 3 (850 CE)<ref>『{{ill|Nihon Montoku Tennō Jitsuroku|ja|日本文徳天皇実録|qq=draft|qq=draft}}』 嘉祥3rd year {{ill|7月11日 (旧暦)|ja|7月11日|qq=draft|qq=draft}}（850th year 8月25日）条</ref> and was further elevated to the Junior Fourth Rank in {{ill|Jōgan (Japan)|ja|貞観|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 2 (860 CE)<ref>『{{ill|Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|ja|日本三代実録|qq=draft|qq=draft}}』 貞観2nd year {{ill|1月27日 (旧暦)|ja|正月27日|qq=draft|qq=draft}}（860th year 2月26日）条</ref>. It was originally located in Yorigo, Sanka District (modern-day Haruno, {{ill|Tenryū-ku|ja|天竜区|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, [[Hamamatsu]]), near the {{ill|Seikoku Rokuon Daibosatsu|ja|正国六音大菩薩社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}<ref>『遠江国風土記伝』</ref>. During the {{ill|Gangyō era|ja|元慶|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 5 (881 CE), the shrine was moved near the provincial capital of Tōtōmi when Sanka District was separated from Iwata District.

By the [[Kamakura period]], the shrine was referred to as Ninomiya. Records from {{ill|Bunei era|ja|文永|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 5 (1268 CE) mention shrine lands under "Tōtōmi Province's Ninomiya Domain."<ref>『基重言上状』</ref> During the [[Edo period]], the shrine served as the [[sōchinju]] for 14 villages, including Ninomiya Village. In the 9th year of {{ill|Genna (Japan)|ja|元和|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (1623 CE), the shrine buildings were rebuilt, as indicated by surviving {{ill|mune-fuda|ja|棟札|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. In the first year of {{ill|Keian era|ja|慶安|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (1648 CE), the shrine was granted 23 koku of land.

