'''Rokuon Shrine''' (鹿苑神社) is a [[:en:Shinto shrine|Shinto shrine]] located in Ninomiya, [[:en:Iwata|Iwata]], [[:en:Shizuoka Prefecture|Shizuoka Prefecture]]. It is classified as a {{ill|Shikinaisha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|2=ja|3=式内社|qq=draft|1=Shikinaisha|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shikinaisha|13=User:Immanuelle|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyocho|lt=Shikinaisha}}, the second shrine (Ninomiya) of [[:en:Tōtōmi Province|Tōtōmi Province]], and was previously Ranked as a {{ill|Gōsha|ja|郷社|1=Gō-sha|qid=Q134917316}}{{efn|District Shrines|lt=Ken-sha|1=modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gōsha|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 近代社格制度|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q712534}} under the old shrine Ranking system.

To the north, it borders Renpuku-ji Temple, and it is situated southeast of [[:en:Iwata Station|Iwata Station]] and south of the Yokosuka Highway. The shrine crest is the "Sixteen Chrysanthemums." Until the late [[:en:Edo period|Edo period]], it was known as "Takane Myōjinja" and enshrined [[:en:Ajisukitakahikone|Takahikone no Mikoto]].

== History ==

The shrine is identified with the {{ill|Kashikojinja|ja|鹿神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kashikojinja|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} mentioned as a minor shrine in the {{ill|Engishiki|ja|延喜式神名帳|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Engishiki|13=User:Immanuelle/Engishiki Jinmyōchō|qq=}} for Iwata District. The deity of Rokuon Shrine was granted the Junior Fifth Rank in [[:en:Kashō|Kashō (Japan)]] 3 (850 CE)<ref>『[[:en:Nihon Montoku Tennō Jitsuroku|Nihon Montoku Tennō Jitsuroku]]』 嘉祥3rd year [[:en:July 11|7月11日 (旧暦)]]（850th year 8月25日）条</ref> and was further elevated to the Junior Fourth Rank in [[:en:Zhenguan|Jōgan (Japan)]] 2 (860 CE)<ref>『[[:en:Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku]]』 貞観2nd year {{ill|1月27日 (旧暦)|1=January 27 (Lunisolar)|2=ja|3=1月27日 (旧暦)|4=zh|5=正月廿七|6=ko|7=음력 1월 27일|ja|正月27日|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1月27日 (旧暦)|1=January 27 (Lunisolar)|2=ja|3=1月27日 (旧暦)|4=zh|5=正月廿七|6=ko|7=음력 1월 27일|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}（860th year 2月26日）条</ref>. It was originally located in Yorigo, Sanka District (modern-day Haruno, [[:en:Tenryū-ku|Tenryū-ku]], [[:en:Hamamatsu|Hamamatsu]]), near the {{ill|Seikoku Rokuon Daibosatsu|ja|正国六音大菩薩社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Seikoku Rokuon Daibosatsu|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}<ref>『遠江国風土記伝』</ref>. During the [[:en:Gangyō|Gangyō era]] 5 (881 CE), the shrine was moved near the provincial capital of Tōtōmi when Sanka District was separated from Iwata District.

By the [[:en:Kamakura period|Kamakura period]], the shrine was referred to as Ninomiya. Records from [[:en:Bun'ei|Bunei era]] 5 (1268 CE) mention shrine lands under "Tōtōmi Province's Ninomiya Domain."<ref>『基重言上状』</ref> During the [[:en:Edo period|Edo period]], the shrine served as the [[sōchinju]] for 14 villages, including Ninomiya Village. In the 9th year of [[:en:Yuanhe|Genna (Japan)]] (1623 CE), the shrine buildings were rebuilt, as indicated by surviving {{ill|Munafuda|lt=Munafuda|lt=Mune-fuda|ja|棟札|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/mune-fuda|qq=}}. In the first year of [[:en:Keian|Keian era]] (1648 CE), the shrine was granted 23 koku of land.

